# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: biophilia-hypothesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold was influential in the development of modern environmental ethics and in the movement for wilderness conservation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His ethics of nature and wildlife preservation had a profound impact on the environmental movement, with his ecocentric or holistic ethics regarding land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He emphasized biodiversity and ecology and was a founder of the science of wildlife management.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo Leopold was born in Burlington, Iowa, on January 11, 1887.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His father, Carl Leopold, was a businessman who made walnut desks and was first cousin to his wife, Clara Starker.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Charles Starker, who was Carl's father and Clara's uncle, came to the United States from Germany and studied engineering and architecture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Rand Aldo was named after two of his father's business partners—C.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Rand and Aldo Sommers—although he eventually dropped the use of "Rand".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Leopold family included younger siblings Mary Luize, Carl Starker, and Frederic.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's first language was German, although he mastered English at an early age.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's early life was highlighted by the outdoors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Carl would take his children on excursions into the woods and taught his oldest son woodcraft and hunting.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Aldo showed an aptitude for observation, spending hours counting and cataloging birds near his home.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His sister Mary later said that even as a young child, "He was very much an outdoorsman, even in his extreme youth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was always out climbing around the bluffs, or going down to the river, or going across the river into the woods." He attended Prospect Hill Elementary, where he ranked at the top of his class, and then, the overcrowded Burlington High School.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Every August, the family vacationed in Michigan on the forested Marquette Island in Lake Huron, which the children took to exploring.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1900, Gifford Pinchot, head of the new Division of Forestry in the Department of Agriculture, donated money to Yale University to begin one of the nation's first forestry schools.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Hearing of this development, teenage Leopold decided he wanted to become a forester.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His parents agreed to let him attend The Lawrenceville School, a preparatory college in New Jersey, to improve his chances of admission to Yale.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Burlington High School principal wrote in a reference letter to the headmaster at Lawrenceville saying that Leopold was "as earnest a boy as we have in school... painstaking in his work....
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Moral character above reproach." He arrived at his new school in January 1904, shortly before he turned 17.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was considered an attentive student, although he was again drawn to the outdoors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Lawrenceville was suitably rural, and Leopold spent much time mapping the area and studying its wildlife.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold studied at the Lawrenceville School for a year, during which time he was accepted to Yale.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Since the Yale School of Forestry granted only graduate degrees, Leopold first enrolled in Sheffield Scientific School's preparatory forestry courses for his undergraduate studies, in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] While Leopold was able to explore the woods and fields of Lawrenceville daily, sometimes to the detriment of his studying, at Yale he had little opportunity to do so; his studies and social life made his outdoor trips few and far between.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold graduated from the Yale Forestry School in 1909.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1909, Leopold was assigned to the Forest Service's District 3 in the Arizona and New Mexico territories.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] At first, he was a forest assistant at the Apache National Forest in the Arizona Territory.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1911, he was transferred to the Carson National Forest in northern New Mexico.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold was stationed in New Mexico until 1924 because he was developing the first comprehensive management plan for the Grand Canyon, writing the Forest Service's first game and fish handbook, and proposing Gila Wilderness Area, the first wilderness area in the Forest Service system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, Leopold encouraged many changes within New Mexico and Arizona through his time spent in the region developing these plans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1916, Leopold conducted a speaking tour across New Mexico to encourage the formation of wildlife protection associations among local sportsmen.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The tour began in Silver City, where Leopold met Miles W.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Buford, who went on to establish the Sportsmen's Association of Southwestern New Mexico.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold proposed the creation of a statewide organization, the New Mexico Game Protection Association (NMGPA), which gained support in several cities including Rincon, El Paso, Alamogordo, Cloudcroft, Carlsbad, Roswell, and Albuquerque.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In March 1916, the NMGPA held its first convention, attracting over 1,000 members.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The association adopted three goals: removing game warden appointments from political influence, establishing game refuges within national forests, and implementing a balance of predators.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Following the formation of the NMGPA, Leopold returned to his duties with the U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] After the passage of the Term Permit Act, he began siting and surveying locations in Arizona for private recreational development.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] During this time, he also promoted and helped establish Game Protection Associations in Arizona towns such as Flagstaff, Springerville, Tucson, and Payson.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In January 1918, Leopold became Secretary of the Albuquerque Chamber of Commerce.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In this role, he supported various initiatives, including the inclusion of labor organizations in the chamber, the promotion of Hispanic and Pueblo architectural styles, and the drainage of parts of the Rio Grande Valley to expand agricultural land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold rejoined the Forest Service on August 1, 1919, as Assistant District Forester in Charge of Operations, overseeing Region 3, which included 11 national forests.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] During this period, he became concerned with soil erosion in areas such as the Prescott and Carson National Forests.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In December 1923, he authored *The Watershed Handbook*, a guide for field staff addressing watershed management and recommending the regulation of livestock based on watershed conditions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Just a few months into his new role, Leopold's superior, District Forester Paul Redington, left Region 3 and was succeeded by Frank C.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Pooler—who openly expressed doubts about Leopold's suitability for the position.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Pooler even arranged a new post for Leopold in a different region.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] However, Leopold stood his ground and declined the offer, choosing to stay in Albuquerque and New Mexico, where his family and numerous ongoing projects were deeply rooted.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's management plan was visionary for its time, emphasizing sustainable use and ecological preservation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He planned to make regulations with tourism, resource protection, recreational planning, and the long-term vision of the park.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He felt that there needed to be a control of commercial enterprises, such as shops and concessions because he described them as "repugnant" to the canyon's natural character.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He suggested there should be designated areas for visitor facilities to minimize environmental disruption.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Additionally, He advocated for the cleanup of garbage and sewage to restore the Colorado River's water quality.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Previously, there was history of people dumping garbage in the river.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He emphasized preserving the canyon's geological and ecological features, including its stratified rock formations and native flora and fauna.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's plan for recreational planning was to outline strategies for “primitive recreation,” such as hiking, hunting, and fishing, to allow visitors to experience the canyon's wilderness without degrading it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He recommended trail development to improve access while protecting sensitive areas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Finally, his long-term vision was to prioritized the “greatest good for the greatest number in the long run,” aligning with U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He laid the groundwork for future park management by advocating for a balance between human enjoyment and ecological health.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Wildlife management was largely unregulated, with game and fish populations often depleted due to overhunting, habitat destruction, and lack of coordinated oversight.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold recognized the need for a systematic approach to manage wildlife resources.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In the handbook, Leopold detailed a section on wildlife population management where he provided a guideline for monitoring and regulating game species, such as deer, elk, and fish, to prevent overharvesting.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He emphasized sustainable hunting and fishing practices to maintain population health.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he wrote a section on habitat conservation which he stressed the importance of preserving habitats, including forests, rivers, and wetlands, to support wildlife.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He included recommendations for mitigating the impacts of grazing and logging on game and fish habitats.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In a section about ecological balance, he introduced early concepts of predator-prey dynamics reflecting on his observations of ecological consequences when predators like wolves were eradicated.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He advocated for a holistic approach to land management considering wildlife as part of the broader ecosystem.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Service rangers to collect data on wildlife populations and enforce regulations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He proposed coordination with local communities and hunters to promote conservation awareness.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1921, Leopold published an article in the *Journal of Forestry* titled “The Wilderness and Its Place in Forest Recreational Policy,” arguing for the preservation of roadless areas within national forests.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He proposed the Gila as a prime candidate, envisioning it as a space free from roads, motorized vehicles, and industrial development.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He recommended setting aside 750,000 acres of the Gila National Forest headwaters, an area characterized by canyons, mesas, and diverse wildlife, including elk, deer, and trout.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's proposal gained traction, and in 1924, the Forest Service approved the designation of 755,000 acres as the Gila Wilderness Area, the first such area in the world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold saw the Gila as a living laboratory for ecological health, where natural processes like predator-prey dynamics could unfold without human interference.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This reflected his early understanding of trophic cascades, later detailed in his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain.” He also valued the Gila for its cultural significance, offering a space for Americans to reconnect with the frontier experience through self-reliant recreation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] On April 5, 1923, he was elected an associate member (now called "professional member") of the Boone and Crockett Club, a wildlife conservation organization founded by Theodore Roosevelt and George Bird Grinnell.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1924, he accepted transfer to the U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Products Laboratory in Madison, Wisconsin, and became an associate director.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1933, he was appointed Professor of Game Management in the Agricultural Economics Department at the University of Wisconsin, the first such professorship of wildlife management.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] At the same time he was named Research Director of the University of Wisconsin–Madison Arboretum.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold and other members of the first Arboretum Committee initiated a research agenda around re-establishing "original Wisconsin" landscape and plant communities, particularly those that predated European settlement, such as tallgrass prairie and oak savanna.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Under the Oberlaender Trust of the Carl Schurz Memorial Foundation, Leopold was part of the 1935 group of six U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Service associates who toured the forests of Germany and Austria.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold was invited specifically to study game management, and this was his first and only time abroad.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His European observations would have a significant impact on his ecological thinking, leading him to view the German policies in favor of blocks of monoculture trees in straight lines as a cautionary tale leading to soil degradation and an overall loss of biodiversity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] After 1935, Leopold was no longer working for the U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Service; he had left the agency in 1928 to work independently and later became a professor at the University of Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold married Estella Bergere, the daughter of a well known ranching family in New Mexico, in northern New Mexico in 1912 and they had five children together.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] They lived in a modest two-story home close to the UW–Madison campus.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His children followed in his footsteps as teachers and naturalists: Aldo Starker Leopold (1913–1983) was a wildlife biologist and professor at UC Berkeley; Luna B.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold purchased 80 acres in the sand country of central Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The once-forested region had been logged, swept by repeated fires, overgrazed by dairy cows, and left barren.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He put his theories to work in the field and eventually set to work writing his best-selling *A Sand County Almanac* (1949) which was finished just prior to his death.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold died from a heart attack on April 21, 1948, while helping his neighbors control a grass fire by his farm in Baraboo, Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's home is an official landmark of the city of Madison.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Early on, Leopold was assigned to hunt and kill bears, wolves, and mountain lions in New Mexico.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Local ranchers hated these predators because of livestock losses, but Leopold came to respect the animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] One day after fatally shooting a wolf, Leopold reached the animal and was transfixed by a "fierce green fire dying in her eyes." That experience changed him and put him on the path toward an ecocentric outlook.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He developed an ecological ethic that replaced the earlier wilderness ethic that stressed the need for human dominance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His rethinking the importance of predators in the balance of nature has resulted in the return of bears and mountain lions to New Mexico wilderness areas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] By the early 1920s, Leopold had concluded that a particular kind of preservation should be embraced in the national forests of the American West.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was prompted to this by the rampant building of roads to accommodate the "proliferation of the automobile" and the related increasingly heavy recreational demands placed on public lands.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was the first to employ the term "wilderness" to describe such preservation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Over the next two decades, he added ethical and scientific rationales to his defense of the wilderness concept.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that it is easier to maintain wilderness than to create it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold thus rejected the utilitarianism of conservationists such as Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] By the 1930s, Leopold had become one of the first Americans to publish extensively on the startup discipline of wildlife management.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He advocated the scientific management of wildlife habitats by both public and private landholders rather than a reliance on game refuges, hunting laws, and other methods intended to protect specific species of desired game.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The concept of "wilderness" also took on a new meaning; Leopold no longer saw it as a hunting or recreational ground, but as an arena for a healthy biotic community, including wolves and mountain lions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1935, he helped found the Wilderness Society, dedicated to expanding and protecting the nation's wilderness areas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He regarded the society as "one of the focal points of a new attitude—an intelligent humility toward Man's place in nature." Science writer Connie Barlow says Leopold wrote eloquently from a perspective that today would be called Religious Naturalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Though often forgotten, thinking about population dynamics and consumption also shaped Leopold's ecological vision in profound ways.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] By studying wildlife population fluctuations, Leopold extended many of the ideas about carrying capacity and environmental degradation that Raymond Pearl and Edward Murray East had articulated, and these ideas, in turn, shaped his path-breaking ideas of ecological interconnection.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Moreover, although later readers associate Leopold with wildlife ecology, his career helps show how Malthusian ideas of human society intertwined and overlapped with ideas of nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was greatly influenced by ecologists who themselves gleaned ideas from Malthusian models of human society, and himself often thought of human events—especially the Great Depression and World War II—in terms of the models of population and consumption that he was developing for animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] One of the most influential books for Leopold during that period was *Our Vanishing Wildlife* by William Temple Hornaday.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] As one of the earliest works dedicated entirely to the threats facing wild game populations this book significantly shaped Leopold's views.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The book sharpened his focus on the importance of game protection, a concern that would remain central to his thinking for many years to come.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's nature writing is notable for its simple directness.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] His portrayals of various natural environments through which he had moved, or had known for many years, displayed impressive intimacy with what exists and happens in nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This includes detailed diaries and journals of his Forest Service activity, hunting and field experience, as well as observations and activities at his Sand County farm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He offered frank criticism of the harm he believed was frequently done to natural systems (such as land) out of a sense of a culture or society's sovereign ownership over the land base – eclipsing any sense of a community of life to which humans belong.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The book was published in 1949, shortly after Leopold's death.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] It was structured in a series of monthly essays where he went in depth about land ethics and nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Several of these monthly essays were accompanied with sketches from the different landscapes and plants he found.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Additionally, he would have philosophical segments that would contribute to his land ethic concepts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Thinking Like a Mountain was originally written during World War II and shows that Leopold's thinking was shaped by that global cataclysm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In "The Land Ethic", a chapter in *A Sand County Almanac*, Leopold delves into conservation in "The Ecological Conscience" section.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He wrote: "Conservation is a state of harmony between men and land." He noted that conservation guidelines at the time boiled down to: "obey the law, vote right, join some organizations, and practice what conservation is profitable on your own land; the government will do the rest." (p.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold's contributions to conservation, particularly his role in establishing the Gila Wilderness Area, are deeply intertwined with the evolution of his philosophical views.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In the early 20th century, Leopold's work with the U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Service in the American Southwest was grounded in the agency's utilitarian ethos, which prioritized resource extraction and economic productivity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] As a forester in Arizona and New Mexico, Leopold initially approached wildlife management with a focus on maximizing game species for human benefit, a perspective aligned with the Progressive Era's emphasis on efficient resource use.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's philosophy began to evolve in the 1910s and 1920s, driven by field observations, ecological consequences of his early practices, and intellectual growth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] A pivotal moment in Leopold's transformation occurred around 1909–1910, during his early years in the Apache National Forest.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In his essay “Thinking Like a Mountain”, Leopold recounts shooting a wolf and watching it die, observing “a fierce green fire” in its eyes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This visceral experience, coupled with witnessing the subsequent ecological fallout, profoundly altered his perspective.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The incident highlighted the role of predators in maintaining ecological balance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Without wolves, deer populations surged, overgrazing vegetation and triggering a cascade of environmental damage, including soil erosion and loss of biodiversity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold realized that “the mountain” required all its components—predators, prey, and plants—to function healthily.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This moment marked a shift from viewing wildlife in isolation to understanding ecosystems as dynamic, interdependent systems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] It planted the seed for his later ecocentric philosophy, where no single species, including humans, could be prioritized at the expense of the whole.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In "Marshland Elegy", an excerpt from *A Sand County Almanac,* Leopold describes the process of destruction for American marshland as well as the efforts to reinvigorate those marshlands after that destruction.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold speak both to the way in which the halting of farmland development in these areas represents positive change for the cranes and other wildlife that relies on marshes as well as the limitations of the strategies implemented by conservationists in the issue.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold criticized conservation strategy in that to make the public cherish the communities we conserve they need to "see and fondle" them which can make the conservation effort self-defeating.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] At the time this essay was written Sandhill Cranes had dwindled to merely 25 breeding pairs in Wisconsin, luckily since then the crane population has recovered with the midwest now being home to over 15,000 sandhill cranes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] These efforts were inspired by this essay and carried out by the Aldo Leopold foundation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] These efforts give a positive example to be looked to for future conservation efforts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Game Management is deemed Leopold's most important work as it founded a new science by combining the likes of agriculture, biology, ecology, and other sciences.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This book brought about a revolution within conservation and placed Leopold as the founder of the Department of Game Management at The University of Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] For more than 40 years after its publication, it was the leading textbook in the field of wildlife management.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Published nearly 45 years after the death of Leopold, The River of the Mother of God, includes 59 essays drawn from Leopold's unpublished manuscripts found at The University of Wisconsin and Leopold's overlooked published work.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This collection is titled after one of Leopold's most popular essays from 1924, “The River of the Mother of God,” but it spans Leopold's life discussing themes of wilderness preservation, ecology, agriculture, land ethics, and natural esthetics from his teenage years until his last years.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This work dives into a deeper view of Leopold and shows the lasting impact he made on the field of conservation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In *A Sand County Almanac*, Aldo Leopold's essay “A Man’s Leisure Time” provides us with a thoughtful examination of how leisure enriches our lives by deepening our connection with nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold believed that how one spends their free time is a good indicator of one's intelligence and character.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold states, “How miserable are the idle hours of the ignorant man!” contributing to his idea that leisure time is meaningful and it is important to take in the nature around when present with the opportunity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] According to Leopold, leisure activities should not be relaxing time but ways to achieve personal growth and understanding.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He describes hobbies as "a defiance of the contemporary," suggesting that they allow individuals to step away from the relentless pace of modern life and engage in activities that are rewarding and enriching.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold highlights that such pursuits, whether it's collecting fossils or cultivating a garden, can lead to a profound appreciation of the land and how important and amazing nature is.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In this chapter, Mr.Leopold encourages the reader to consider what they do with their free or leisure time in their life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold advocates for activities that promote a deeper understanding of the natural world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1933, Aldo Leopold became Professor of Game Management at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, the first position of its kind in the country.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Through his contributions to and knowledge of the field, he developed curricula and ran the program, which was eventually redubbed Wildlife Ecology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] "Game Management" during this time meant the scientific study and the practical application of techniques for maintaining a healthy wildlife population, especially those that are hunted for sport.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Through his expertise, the area of wildlife management grew from just managing populations within life to a larger egocialcal approach to managing wildlife population.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Game management was a branch of conservation biology to Aldo Leopold.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was concerned about the whole ecological balance of the environment and not just one species.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He created a field that was hit every area ecology, policy, forestry, and ethics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He even published a textbook for his class titles "Game management", also published in 1933.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1950 The Wildlife Society honored Leopold by creating an annual award in his name.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Furthermore, the foundation formed a Leopold Conservation Award to recognize farmers, forestland owners, and private land owners for inspirational conservation efforts and leadership within land ethics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The *Aldo Leopold Foundation* of Baraboo, Wisconsin, was founded in 1982 by Aldo and Estella Leopold's five children as a 501(c)3 not-for-profit conservation organization whose mission is "to foster the land ethic through the legacy of Aldo Leopold".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Foundation owns and manages the original Aldo Leopold Shack and Farm and 300 surrounding acres, in addition to several other parcels.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Its headquarters is the green-built *Leopold Center* where it conducts educational and land stewardship programs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The foundation also acts as the executor of Leopold's literary estate, encourages scholarship on Leopold, and serves as a clearinghouse for information regarding Leopold, his work, and his ideas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] It provides interpretive resources and tours for thousands of visitors annually, distributes a curriculum about how to use Leopold's writing and ideas in environmental education.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The center maintains a robust website and numerous print resources.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 2012, in collaboration with the United States Forest Service, the foundation and the Center for Humans and Nature released the first full-length film about Leopold, titled *Green Fire: Aldo Leopold and a Land Ethic for Our Time*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The film aired on public television stations across the nation and won a Midwest regional Emmy award in the documentary category.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Wilderness in New Mexico's Gila National Forest was named after him in 1980.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture was established in 1987 at Iowa State University in Ames.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Since its founding, it has pioneered new forms of sustainable agriculture practices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Forest Service established the Aldo Leopold Wilderness Research Institute at the University of Montana, Missoula in 1993.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Neighborhood Historic District, which includes Leopold's former home in Albuquerque, New Mexico, was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2002.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Aldo Leopold Legacy Trail System, a system of 42 state trails in Wisconsin, was created by the state in 2007 to honor Leopold's contributions to the conservation and outdoor recreation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This trail covers more than 1,700 miles across the state of Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Many of the trails pass through forests, scenics natural areas, and state parks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] There are signs, along the trails, to showcase information about Leopold's life, his conservation work, and natural information about the surrounding area.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Center for Sustainable Agriculture in Iowa, created through the 1987 Iowa Groundwater Protection Act is committed to "new ways to farm profitably while conserving natural resources as well as reducing negative environmental and social impacts".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] An organization, the Leopold Heritage Group, is "dedicated to promoting the global legacy of Aldo Leopold in his hometown of Burlington, Iowa." This groups preserves and shares Leopold's legacy by providing local events, educational programs, and conservation projects.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The "Leopold Heritage Group", supports efforts to maintain Leopold-relates sites around the area for example, his childhood home and many places that he has explored as a child.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] In 1985, Leopold was inducted along with John Muir, a naturalist and preservationist, as the first inductees to the Wisconsin Conservation Hall of Fame.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Hall of Fame is located in Stevens Point, Wisconsin, it was created to recognize the individuals who have made important contributions to conserving the natural state of resources around the state.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] The Leopold Residence Hall at the University of Wisconsin-Madison was named after him.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Leopold's Preserve in Haymarket, Virginia was established in 2014.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] This preserve is a 380-acre park that is committed to preserving diverse ecosystems, natural scenes, and protecting threatened land from industrial and commercial development.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] Aldo Leopold is well known for being the founder of wildlife management, he played a key role in establishing ethics in the wildlife world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/aldo-leopold] He was a driving force behind the creation of the Gila National Forest Wilderness, and his legacy lives on today as the Gila National Forest has been standing strong since 1924, when the National Forest was created.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] To be counted as a true migration, and not just a local dispersal or irruption, the movement of the animals should be an annual or seasonal occurrence, or a major habitat change as part of their life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] An annual event could include Northern Hemisphere birds migrating south for the winter, or wildebeest migrating annually for seasonal grazing.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] A major habitat change could include young Atlantic salmon or sea lamprey leaving the river of their birth when they have reached a few inches in size.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some traditional forms of human migration fit this pattern.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Migrations can be studied using traditional identification tags such as bird rings, or tracked directly with electronic tracking devices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Before animal migration was understood, folklore explanations were formulated for the appearance and disappearance of some species, such as that barnacle geese grew from goose barnacles.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Migration can take very different forms in different species, and has a variety of causes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] As such, there is no simple accepted definition of migration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] One of the most commonly used definitions, proposed by the zoologist J.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Migration can be either obligate, meaning individuals must migrate, or facultative, meaning individuals can "choose" to migrate or not.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Within a migratory species or even within a single population, often not all individuals migrate.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] *Complete migration* is when all individuals migrate, *partial migration* is when some individuals migrate while others do not, and *differential migration* is when the difference between migratory and non-migratory individuals is based on discernible characteristics like age or sex.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Irregular (non-cyclical) migrations such as irruptions can occur under pressure of famine, overpopulation of a locality, or some more obscure influence.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Seasonal migration is the movement of various species from one habitat to another during the year.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Resource availability changes depending on seasonal fluctuations, which influence migration patterns.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some species such as Pacific salmon migrate to reproduce; every year, they swim upstream to mate and then return to the ocean.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Temperature is a driving factor of migration that is dependent on the time of year.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Many species, especially birds, migrate to warmer locations during the winter to escape poor environmental conditions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Circadian migration is where birds utilise circadian rhythm (CR) to regulate migration in both fall and spring.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] In circadian migration, clocks of both circadian (daily) and circannual (annual) patterns are used to determine the birds' orientation in both time and space as they migrate from one destination to the next.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] This type of migration is advantageous in birds that, during the winter, remain close to the equator, and also allows the monitoring of the auditory and spatial memory of the bird's brain to remember an optimal site of migration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] These birds also have timing mechanisms that provide them with the distance to their destination.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Tidal migration is the use of tides by organisms to move periodically from one habitat to another.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] This type of migration is often used in order to find food or mates.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Tides can carry organisms horizontally and vertically for as little as a few nanometres to even thousands of kilometres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The most common form of tidal migration is to and from the intertidal zone during daily tidal cycles.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] These zones are often populated by many different species and are rich in nutrients.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Organisms like crabs, nematodes, and small fish move in and out of these areas as the tides rise and fall, typically about every twelve hours.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The cycle movements are associated with foraging of marine and bird species.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Typically, during low tide, smaller or younger species will emerge to forage because they can survive in the shallower water and have less chance of being preyed upon.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] During high tide, larger species can be found due to the deeper water and nutrient upwelling from the tidal movements.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Tidal migration is often facilitated by ocean currents.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] While most migratory movements occur on an annual cycle, some daily movements are also described as migration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Many aquatic animals make a diel vertical migration, travelling a few hundred metres up and down the water column, while some jellyfish make daily horizontal migrations of a few hundred metres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Different kinds of animals migrate in different ways.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Approximately 1,800 of the world's 10,000 bird species migrate long distances each year in response to the seasons.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Many of these migrations are north-south, with species feeding and breeding in high northern latitudes in the summer and moving some hundreds of kilometres south for the winter.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some species extend this strategy to migrate annually between the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The Arctic tern has the longest migration journey of any bird: it flies from its Arctic breeding grounds to the Antarctic and back again each year, a distance of at least 19,000 km (12,000 mi), giving it two summers every year.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Bird migration is controlled primarily by day length, signalled by hormonal changes in the bird's body.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] On migration, birds navigate using multiple senses.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Many birds use a sun compass, requiring them to compensate for the sun's changing position with time of day.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Navigation involves the ability to detect magnetic fields.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Most fish species are relatively limited in their movements, remaining in a single geographical area and making short migrations to overwinter, to spawn, or to feed.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] A few hundred species migrate long distances, in some cases of thousands of kilometres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] About 120 species of fish, including several species of salmon, migrate between saltwater and freshwater (they are 'diadromous').
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Forage fish such as herring and capelin migrate around substantial parts of the North Atlantic ocean.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The capelin, for example, spawn around the southern and western coasts of Iceland; their larvae drift clockwise around Iceland, while the fish swim northwards towards Jan Mayen island to feed and return to Iceland parallel with Greenland's east coast.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] In the 'sardine run', billions of Southern African pilchard *Sardinops sagax* spawn in the cold waters of the Agulhas Bank and move northward along the east coast of South Africa between May and July.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some winged insects such as locusts and certain butterflies and dragonflies with strong flight migrate long distances.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Among the dragonflies, species of *Libellula* and *Sympetrum* are known for mass migration, while *Pantala flavescens*, known as the globe skimmer or wandering glider dragonfly, makes the longest ocean crossing of any insect: between India and Africa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Exceptionally, swarms of the desert locust, *Schistocerca gregaria*, flew westwards across the Atlantic Ocean for 4,500 kilometres (2,800 mi) during October 1988, using air currents in the Inter-Tropical Convergence Zone.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] In some migratory butterflies, such as the monarch butterfly and the painted lady, no individual completes the whole migration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Instead, the butterflies mate and reproduce on the journey, and successive generations continue the migration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some mammals undertake exceptional migrations; reindeer have one of the longest terrestrial migrations on the planet, reaching as much as 4,868 kilometres (3,025 mi) per year in North America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] However, over the course of a year, grey wolves move the most.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] One grey wolf covered a total cumulative annual distance of 7,247 kilometres (4,503 mi).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Mass migration occurs in mammals such as the Serengeti 'great migration', an annual circular pattern of movement with some 1.7 million wildebeest and hundreds of thousands of other large game animals, including gazelles and zebra.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] More than 20 such species engage, or used to engage, in mass migrations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Of these migrations, those of the springbok, black wildebeest, blesbok, scimitar-horned oryx, and kulan have ceased.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Long-distance migrations occur in some bats, such as the mass migration of the Mexican free-tailed bat between Oregon and southern Mexico.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Migration is important in cetaceans, including whales, dolphins and porpoises; some species travel long distances between their feeding and their breeding areas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Humans are mammals, but human migration, as commonly defined, is when individuals often permanently change where they live, which does not fit the patterns described here.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] An exception is some traditional migratory patterns such as transhumance, in which herders and their animals move seasonally between mountains and valleys, and the seasonal movements of nomads.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Among the reptiles, adult sea turtles migrate long distances to breed, as do some amphibians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Hatchling sea turtles, too, emerge from underground nests, crawl down to the water, and swim offshore to reach the open sea.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Juvenile green sea turtles make use of Earth's magnetic field to navigate.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Some crustaceans migrate, such as the largely-terrestrial Christmas Island red crab, which moves en masse each year by the millions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Like other crabs, they breathe using gills, which must remain wet, so they avoid direct sunlight, digging burrows to shelter from the sun.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The females incubate their eggs in their abdominal brood pouches for two weeks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Then they return to the sea to release their eggs at high tide in the moon's last quarter.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The larvae spend a few weeks at sea and then return to land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Scientists gather observations of animal migration by tracking their movements.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Animals were traditionally tracked with identification tags such as bird rings for later recovery.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] However, no information was obtained about the actual route followed between release and recovery, and only a fraction of tagged individuals were recovered.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] More convenient, therefore, are electronic devices such as radio-tracking collars that can be followed by radio, whether handheld, in a vehicle or aircraft, or by satellite.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] GPS animal tracking enables accurate positions to be broadcast at regular intervals, but the devices are inevitably heavier and more expensive than those without GPS.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] An alternative is the Argos Doppler tag, also called a 'Platform Transmitter Terminal' (PTT), which sends regularly to the polar-orbiting Argos satellites; using Doppler shift, the animal's location can be estimated, relatively roughly compared to GPS, but at a lower cost and weight.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] A technology suitable for small birds which cannot carry the heavier devices is the geolocator which logs the light level as the bird flies, for analysis on recapture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] There is scope for further development of systems able to track small animals globally.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Radio-tracking tags can be fitted to insects, including dragonflies and bees.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Before animal migration was understood, various folklore and erroneous explanations were formulated to account for the disappearance or sudden arrival of birds in an area.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] In Ancient Greece, Aristotle proposed that robins turned into redstarts when summer arrived.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] The barnacle goose was explained in European Medieval bestiaries and manuscripts as either growing like fruit on trees, or developing from goose barnacles on pieces of driftwood.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal-migration] Another example is the swallow, which was once thought, even by naturalists such as Gilbert White, to hibernate either underwater, buried in muddy riverbanks, or in hollow trees.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Although each culture has its own mythologies and rituals, animism is said to describe the most common, foundational thread of indigenous peoples' "spiritual" or "supernatural" perspectives.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The animistic perspective is so widely held and inherent to most indigenous peoples that they often do not even have a word in their languages that corresponds to "animism" (or even "religion").
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The term "animism" is an anthropological construct.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] According to a 2016 study, the oldest traits and most recent common ancestors' beliefs was animism, which would influence the later development of human religions in unseen forces, realms and spiritual beings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Largely due to such ethnolinguistic and cultural discrepancies, opinions differ on whether animism refers to an ancestral mode of experience common to indigenous peoples around the world or to a full-fledged religion in its own right.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The accepted definition of animism was developed only in the late 19th century (1871) by Edward Tylor.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] It is "one of anthropology's earliest concepts, if not the first".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Examples include water sprites, vegetation deities, and tree spirits, among others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism may further attribute a life force to abstract concepts such as words, true names, or metaphors in mythology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Some members of the non-tribal world also consider themselves animists, such as author Daniel Quinn, sculptor Lawson Oyekan, and many neopagans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] English anthropologist Sir Edward Tylor initially wanted to describe the phenomenon as spiritualism, but he realized that it would cause confusion with the modern religion of spiritualism, which was then prevalent across Western nations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The first known usage in English appeared in 1819.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Earlier anthropological perspectives, which have since been termed the old animism, were concerned with knowledge on what is alive and what factors make something alive.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The old animism assumed that animists were individuals who were unable to understand the difference between persons and things.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The idea of animism was developed by anthropologist Sir Edward Tylor through his 1871 book *Primitive culture*, in which he defined it as "the general doctrine of souls and other spiritual beings in general".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] According to Tylor, animism often includes "an idea of pervading life and will in nature"; a belief that natural objects other than humans have souls.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] This formulation was little different from that proposed by Auguste Comte as "fetishism", but the terms now have distinct meanings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For Tylor, animism represented the earliest form of religion, situated within an evolutionary framework of religion that has developed in stages and which will ultimately lead to humanity rejecting religion altogether in favor of scientific rationality.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Thus, for Tylor, animism was fundamentally seen as a mistake, a basic error from which all religions grew.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] He did not believe that animism was inherently illogical; he suggested that it arose from early humans' dreams and visions and thus was a rational system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] However, it was based on erroneous, unscientific observations about the nature of reality.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Tylor's definition of animism was part of a growing international debate on the nature of "primitive society" by lawyers, theologians, and philologists.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The debate defined the field of research of a new science: *anthropology*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] By the end of the 19th century, an orthodoxy on "primitive society" had emerged, but few anthropologists still would accept that definition.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The "19th-century armchair anthropologists" argued that "primitive society" (an evolutionary category) was ordered by kinship and divided into exogamous descent groups related by a series of marriage exchanges.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Their religion was animism, the belief that natural species and objects had souls.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] With the development of private property, the descent groups were displaced by the emergence of the territorial state.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] These rituals and beliefs eventually evolved over time into the vast array of "developed" religions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] According to Tylor, as society became more scientifically advanced, fewer members of that society would believe in animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] However, any remnant ideologies of souls or spirits, to Tylor, represented "survivals" of the original animism of early humanity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In 1869 (three years after Tylor proposed his definition of animism), Edinburgh lawyer John Ferguson McLennan, argued that the animistic thinking evident in fetishism gave rise to a religion he named *totemism*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Primitive people believed, he argued, that they were descended from the same species as their totemic animal.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Subsequent debate by the "armchair anthropologists" (including J.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Bachofen, Émile Durkheim, and Sigmund Freud) remained focused on totemism rather than animism, with few directly challenging Tylor's definition.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Certain indigenous religious groups such as the Aboriginal Australians are more typically totemic in their worldview, whereas others like the Inuit are more typically animistic.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Many anthropologists ceased using the term *animism*, deeming it to be too close to early anthropological theory and religious polemic.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The *new animism* emerged largely from the publications of anthropologist Irving Hallowell, produced on the basis of his ethnographic research among the Ojibwe communities of Canada in the mid-20th century.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For the Ojibwe encountered by Hallowell, *personhood* did not require human-likeness, but rather humans were perceived as being like other persons, who for instance included rock persons and bear persons.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Hallowell's approach to the understanding of Ojibwe personhood differed strongly from prior anthropological concepts of animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] He emphasized the need to challenge the modernist, Western perspectives of what a person is, by entering into a dialogue with different worldwide views.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Hallowell's approach influenced the work of anthropologist Nurit Bird-David, who produced a scholarly article reassessing the idea of animism in 1999.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Seven comments from other academics were provided in the journal, debating Bird-David's ideas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] More recently, postmodern anthropologists are increasingly engaging with the concept of animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Modernism is characterized by a Cartesian subject-object dualism that divides the subjective from the objective, and culture from nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the modernist view, animism is the inverse of scientism, and hence, is deemed inherently invalid by some anthropologists.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Drawing on the work of Bruno Latour, some anthropologists question modernist assumptions and theorize that all societies continue to "animate" the world around them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In contrast to Tylor's reasoning, however, this "animism" is considered to be more than just a remnant of primitive thought.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] More specifically, the "animism" of modernity is characterized by humanity's "professional subcultures", as in the ability to treat the world as a detached entity within a delimited sphere of activity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Human beings continue to create personal relationships with elements of the aforementioned objective world, such as pets, cars, or teddy bears, which are recognized as subjects.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] She explains that animism is a "relational epistemology" rather than a failure of primitive reasoning.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] That is, self-identity among animists is based on their relationships with others, rather than any distinctive features of the "self".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Instead of focusing on the essentialized, modernist self (the "individual"), persons are viewed as bundles of social relationships ("dividuals"), some of which include "superpersons" (i.e. non-humans).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Rane Willerslev extends the argument by noting that animists reject this Cartesian dualism and that the animist self identifies with the world, "feeling at once *within* and *apart* from it so that the two glide ceaselessly in and out of each other in a sealed circuit".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The animist hunter is thus aware of himself as a human hunter, but, through mimicry, is able to assume the viewpoint, senses, and sensibilities of his prey, to be one with it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Shamanism, in this view, is an everyday attempt to influence spirits of ancestors and animals, by mirroring their behaviors, as the hunter does its prey.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Cultural ecologist and philosopher David Abram proposed an ethical and ecological understanding of animism, grounded in the phenomenology of sensory experience.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the absence of intervening technologies, he suggests that sensory experience is inherently animistic in that it discloses a material field that is animate and self-organizing from the beginning.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] David Abram used contemporary cognitive and natural science, as well as the perspectival worldviews of diverse indigenous oral cultures, to propose a richly pluralist and story-based cosmology in which matter is alive.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In contrast to a long-standing tendency in the Western social sciences, which commonly provides rational explanations of animistic experience, Abram develops an animistic account of reason itself.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] He holds that civilised reason is sustained only by intensely animistic participation between human beings and their own written signs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For instance, as soon as someone reads letters on a page or screen, they can "see what it says"—the letters speak as much as nature spoke to pre-literate peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Reading can usefully be understood as an intensely concentrated form of animism, one that effectively eclipses all of the other, older, more spontaneous forms of animistic participation in which humans were once engaged.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In his *Handbook of Contemporary Animism* (2013), Harvey identifies the animist perspective in line with Martin Buber's "I-thou" as opposed to "I-it".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In such, Harvey says, the animist takes an I-thou approach to relating to the world, whereby objects and animals are treated as a "thou", rather than as an "it".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] There is ongoing disagreement (and no general consensus) as to whether animism is merely a singular, broadly encompassing religious belief or a worldview in and of itself, comprising many diverse mythologies found worldwide in many diverse cultures.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] This also raises a controversy regarding the ethical claims animism may or may not make: whether animism ignores questions of ethics altogether; or, by endowing various non-human elements of nature with spirituality or personhood, it in fact promotes a complex ecological ethics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In his 1992 book entitled *Columbus and Other Cannibals*, American historian Jack D.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism is not the same as pantheism, although the two are sometimes confused.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Moreover, some religions are both pantheistic and animistic.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] One of the main differences is that while animists believe everything to be spiritual in nature, they do not necessarily see the spiritual nature of everything in existence as being united (monism) the way pantheists do.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] As a result, animism puts more emphasis on the uniqueness of each individual soul.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In pantheism, everything shares the same spiritual essence, rather than having distinct spirits or souls.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For example, Giordano Bruno equated the world soul with God and espoused a pantheistic animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In many animistic world views, the human being is often regarded as on a roughly equal footing with other animals, plants, and natural forces.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Traditional African religions: most religious traditions of Sub-Saharan Africa are basically a complex form of animism with polytheistic and shamanistic elements and ancestor worship.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In West Africa, the Serer religious (A ƭat Roog) encompasses ancestor veneration (not worship) via the Pangool.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Pangool are the Serer ancestral spirits and interceders between the living and the Divine, Roog.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In East Africa, the Kerma culture displays animistic elements similar to other Traditional African religions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In contrast to the later polytheistic Napatan and Meroitic periods, the Kerma culture, with displays of animals in Amulets and the esteemed antiques of Lions, appears to be an Animistic culture rather than a polytheistic culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Kermans likely treated Jebel Barkal as a special sacred site, and passed it on to the Kushites and Egyptians who venerated the mesa.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In North Africa, the traditional Berber religion includes the traditional polytheistic, animist, and in some rare cases, shamanistic, religions of the Berber people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the Indian-origin religions, namely Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism, and Sikhism, the animistic aspects of nature worship and ecological conservation are part of the core belief system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Matsya Purana, a Hindu text, has a Sanskrit language shloka (hymn), which explains the importance of reverence of ecology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The banyan is considered holy in several religious traditions of India.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The *Ficus benghalensis* is the national tree of India.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Vat Purnima is a Hindu festival related to the banyan tree, and is observed by married women in North India and in the Western Indian states of Maharashtra, Goa, Gujarat.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For three days of the month of Jyeshtha in the Hindu calendar (which falls in May–June in the Gregorian calendar) married women observe a fast, tie threads around a banyan tree, and pray for the well-being of their husbands.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Thimmamma Marrimanu, sacred to Indian religions, has branches spread over five acres and was listed as the world's largest banyan tree in the Guinness World Records in 1989.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In Hinduism, the leaf of the banyan tree is said to be the resting place for the god Krishna.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the Bhagavat Gita, Krishna said, "There is a banyan tree which has its roots upward and its branches down, and the Vedic hymns are its leaves.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In Buddhism's Pali canon, the banyan (Pali: *nigrodha*) is referenced numerous times.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Typical metaphors allude to the banyan's epiphytic nature, likening the banyan's supplanting of a host tree as comparable to the way sensual desire (*kāma*) overcomes humans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Mun (also known as Munism or Bongthingism) is the traditional polytheistic, animist, shamanistic, and syncretic religion of the Lepcha people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Sanamahism is an ethnic religion of the Meitei people of *Kangleipak* (Meitei for 'Manipur') in Northeast India.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] It is a polytheistic and animist religion and is named after Lainingthou Sanamahi, one of the most important deities of the Meitei faith.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Shendao (Chinese: 神道; pinyin: *shéndào*; lit.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] 'the Way of the Gods') is a term originated by Chinese folk religions influenced by, Mohist, Confucian and Taoist philosophy, referring to the divine order of nature or the Wuxing.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Shang dynasty's state religion was practiced from 1600 BCE to 1046 BCE, and was built on the idea of spiritualizing natural phenomena.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Shinto is the traditional Japanese folk religion and has many animist aspects.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The *kami* (神), a class of supernatural beings, are central to Shinto.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] All things, including natural forces and well-known geographical locations, are thought to be home to the kami.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The kami are worshipped at kamidana household shrines, family shrines, and jinja public shrines.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Ryukyuan religion of the Ryukyu Islands is distinct from Shinto, but shares similar characteristics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Kalash people of Northern Pakistan follow an ancient animistic religion identified with an ancient form of Hinduism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Kalash (Kalasha: کالؕاشؕا, romanised: *Kaḷaṣa*, Devanagari: कळष), or Kalasha, are an Indo-Aryan indigenous people residing in the Chitral District of the Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa province of Pakistan.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] They are considered unique among the people of Pakistan.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] They are also considered to be Pakistan's smallest ethnoreligious group, and traditionally practice what authors characterise as a form of animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] During the mid-20th century an attempt was made to force a few Kalasha villages in Pakistan to convert to Islam, but the people fought the conversion and, once official pressure was removed, the vast majority resumed the practice of their own religion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Nevertheless, some Kalasha have since converted to Islam, despite being shunned afterward by their community for having done so.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The term is used to refer to many distinct people including the Väi, the Čima-nišei, the Vântä, plus the Ashkun- and Tregami-speakers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Kalash are considered to be an indigenous people of Asia, with their ancestors migrating to Chitral Valley from another location possibly further south, which the Kalash call "Tsiyam" in their folk songs and epics.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] They claim to descend from the armies of Alexander who were left behind from his armed campaign, though no evidence exists for him to have passed the area.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The neighbouring Nuristani people of the adjacent Nuristan (historically known as Kafiristan) province of Afghanistan once had the same culture and practised a faith very similar to that of the Kalash, differing in a few minor particulars.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The first historically recorded Islamic invasions of their lands were by the Ghaznavids in the 11th century while they themselves are first attested in 1339 during Timur's invasions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Nuristan had been forcibly converted to Islam in 1895–96, although some evidence has shown the people continued to practice their customs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Kalash of Chitral have maintained their own separate cultural traditions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Muism, the native Korean belief, has many animist aspects.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The various deities, called *kwisin,* are capable of interacting with humans and causing problems if they are not honoured appropriately.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In ancient Philippine animism, Diwata or Diwatas in plural is a broad, gender-neutral term for supernatural beings, including gods, goddesses, fairies, nature spirits, and celestial entities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Rooted in Hindu-Buddhist influences, the word originally meant "celestial being" or "descent" in Sanskrit word devata (deity).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In modern Filipino culture, Diwata is often interpreted and linked to fairies, muses, nymphs, or even dryads.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Anito are the wooden statues and ancestor spirits in the various indigenous shamanistic folk religions of the Philippines, led by female or feminized male shamans known as *babaylan*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] It includes belief in a spirit world existing alongside and interacting with the material world, as well as the belief that everything has a spirit, from rocks and trees to animals and humans to natural phenomena.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In indigenous Filipino belief, the Bathala is the omnipotent deity, which was derived from Sanskrit word for the Hindu supreme deity *bhattara*, as one of the ten avatars of the Hindu god Vishnu.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The omnipotent Bathala also presides over the spirits of ancestors called Anito.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Anitos serve as intermediaries between mortals and the divine, such as Agni (Hindu) who holds the access to divine realms; for this reason they are invoked first and are the first to receive offerings, regardless of the deity the worshipper wants to pray to.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism also has influences in Abrahamic religions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Old Testament and the Wisdom literature preach the omnipresence of God (Jeremiah 23:24; Proverbs 15:3; 1 Kings 8:27), and God is bodily present in the incarnation of his Son, Jesus Christ.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism is not peripheral to Christian identity but is its nurturing home ground, its axis mundi.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In addition to the conceptual work the term *animism* performs, it provides insight into the relational character and common personhood of material existence.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Christian spiritual mapping movement is based upon a similar worldview to that of animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] It involves researching and mapping the spiritual and social history of an area in order to determine the demon (territorial spirit) controlling an area and preventing evangelism, so that the demon can be defeated through spiritual warfare prayer and rituals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Both posit that an invisible spirit world is active and that it can be interacted with or controlled, with the Christian belief that such power to control the spirit world comes from God rather than being inherent to objects or places.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] "The animist believes that rituals and objects *contain* spiritual power, whereas a Christian believes that rituals and objects may *convey* power.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] With rising awareness of ecological preservation, recently theologians like Mark I.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Wallace argue for animistic Christianity with a biocentric approach that understands God being present in all earthly objects, such as animals, trees, and rocks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Pre-Islamic Arab religion can refer to the traditional polytheistic, animist, and in some rare cases, shamanistic, religions of the peoples of the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The belief in jinn, invisible entities akin to spirits in the Western sense dominant in the Arab religious systems, hardly fit the description of Animism in a strict sense.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The jinn are considered to be analogous to the human soul by living lives like that of humans, but they are not exactly like human souls neither are they spirits of the dead.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] It is unclear if belief in jinn derived from nomadic or sedentary populations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism has been identified as a foundational element in the development of many ancient and modern pagan religious traditions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] As one of the earliest spiritual worldviews, animism is characterized by the belief that elements of the natural world—including animals, plants, geographical features, and weather systems—possess spirit or agency.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Scholars have noted that this perspective influenced the cosmologies of numerous pre-modern societies and contributed to the development of polytheistic and nature-based religious systems that are now categorized as Pagan traditions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In various ancient cultures, such as those of the Celts, Norse, Greeks, Romans, and Slavs, religious beliefs often incorporated elements now associated with animism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Natural features were frequently regarded as sacred or inhabited by spiritual beings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Deities were often linked to specific rivers, trees, mountains, or celestial bodies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] According to historian Ronald Hutton, nature in these contexts was not only revered but considered to be "alive and participatory" in religious life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] While these societies developed organized pantheons and mythological systems, many retained a view of the natural world that reflected animistic thought.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Practices such as offering rituals at springs, maintaining sacred groves, or acknowledging local land spirits illustrate the integration of animistic concepts within broader polytheistic frameworks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Following the spread of monotheistic religions, especially Christianity, across much of Europe, many animistic and Pagan practices were suppressed or reinterpreted.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Nevertheless, aspects of animistic belief persisted through folk religion, particularly in rural communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Customs such as venerating household spirits, seasonal festivals tied to agricultural cycles, and the personification of natural phenomena continued in modified forms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] For example, certain wells and springs that were originally associated with local deities came to be associated with Christian saints, suggesting a degree of continuity between animistic and Christian devotional practices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] These continuities were often preserved through oral traditions, local rituals, and folk customs, contributing to the survival of animistic perspectives beyond their original religious contexts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The 19th and 20th centuries saw renewed interest in pre-Christian religions and folklore, influenced by Romanticism, antiquarian studies, and the emergence of national identities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] This cultural movement laid the groundwork for contemporary Pagan traditions, such as Wicca, Druidry, and Heathenry, which often draw upon animistic concepts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Some scholars and practitioners of modern Paganism incorporate animism into their religious frameworks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Graham Harvey has noted that contemporary Pagan worldviews frequently emphasize relationality and agency within the natural world, viewing humans as part of a larger network of sentient beings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In Wiccan and other Pagan rituals, for example, elements such as earth, air, fire, and water are invoked not only symbolically but as active, spiritually significant forces.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] This approach reflects an animistic orientation toward the environment.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In recent decades, animism has been reimagined in both academic and spiritual circles.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Rather than viewing it simply as a set of beliefs, many modern interpretations understand animism as a *relational ontology*—a way of being that centers on relationships and mutual respect between humans and non-human entities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] This approach presents animism as a legitimate and coherent worldview, one that offers an alternative to Cartesian dualism and materialist perspectives by emphasizing connection over separation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Emma Restall Orr, a British author and Druidic practitioner, has argued that animism provides a philosophical basis for environmental ethics and personal spirituality within contemporary Paganism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Similarly, Sabina Magliocco has documented the presence of animistic themes in American Neo-Pagan practices, including rituals, festivals, and magical systems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Contemporary expressions of animism often align with ecological values, highlighting themes like sustainability, interdependence, and a deep respect for the natural world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Within this context, animism is no longer seen as outdated or primitive, but as a meaningful way for people to engage with both their environment and the spiritual forces they perceive within it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The New Age movement, for instance, often incorporates animistic elements, such as beliefs in nature spirits and energetic connections with the Earth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In recent years, animism has also found a place within emerging spiritual paths.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Many neopagan groups—including Eco-pagans—identify as animists, expressing reverence for the web of life and the unseen presences they believe share the world and cosmos with humanity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] A shaman is a person regarded as having access to, and influence in, the world of benevolent and malevolent spirits, who typically enters into a trance state during a ritual, and practices divination and healing.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] According to Mircea Eliade, shamanism encompasses the premise that shamans are intermediaries or messengers between the human world and the spirit worlds.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Shamans are said to treat ailments and illnesses by mending the soul.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Alleviating traumas affecting the soul or spirit restores the physical body of the individual to balance and wholeness.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The shaman also enters supernatural realms or dimensions to obtain solutions to problems afflicting the community.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Shamans may visit other worlds or dimensions to bring guidance to misguided souls and to ameliorate illnesses of the human soul caused by foreign elements.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The shaman operates primarily within the spiritual world, which in turn affects the human world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The restoration of balance results in the elimination of the ailment.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Abram, however, articulates a less supernatural and much more ecological understanding of the shaman's role than that propounded by Eliade.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Hence, the shaman's ability to heal individual instances of disease (or imbalance) within the human community is a byproduct of their more continual practice of balancing the reciprocity between the human community and the wider collective of animate beings in which that community is embedded.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism entails the belief that all living things have a soul, and thus, a central concern of animist thought surrounds how animals can be eaten, or otherwise used for humans' subsistence needs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The actions of non-human animals are viewed as "intentional, planned and purposive", and they are understood to be persons, as they are both alive, and communicate with others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In animist worldviews, non-human animals are understood to participate in kinship systems and ceremonies with humans, as well as having their own kinship systems and ceremonies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Graham Harvey cited an example of an animist understanding of animal behavior that occurred at a powwow held by the Conne River Mi'kmaq in 1996; an eagle flew over the proceedings, circling over the central drum group.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The assembled participants called out *kitpu* ('eagle'), conveying welcome to the bird and expressing pleasure at its beauty, and they later articulated the view that the eagle's actions reflected its approval of the event, and the Mi'kmaq's return to traditional spiritual practices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In animism, rituals are performed to maintain relationships between humans and spirits.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Indigenous peoples often perform these rituals to appease the spirits and request their assistance during activities such as hunting and healing.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the Arctic region, certain rituals are common before the hunt as a means to show respect for the spirits of animals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Some animists also view plant and fungi life as persons and interact with them accordingly.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The most common encounter between humans and these plant and fungi persons is with the former's collection of the latter for food, and for animists, this interaction typically has to be carried out respectfully.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Harvey cited the example of Māori communities in New Zealand, who often offer *karakia* invocations to sweet potatoes as they dig up the latter.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] While doing so, there is an awareness of a kinship relationship between the Māori and the sweet potatoes, with both understood as having arrived in Aotearoa together in the same canoes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In other instances, animists believe that interaction with plant and fungi persons can result in the communication of things unknown or even otherwise unknowable.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Various animistic cultures also comprehend stones as persons.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The Ojibwe conceived of weather as being capable of having personhood, with storms being conceived of as persons known as 'Thunderers' whose sounds conveyed communications and who engaged in seasonal conflict over the lakes and forests, throwing lightning at lake monsters.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Wind, similarly, can be conceived as a person in animistic thought.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The importance of place is also a recurring element of animism, with some places being understood to be persons in their own right.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animism can also entail relationships being established with non-corporeal spirit entities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] From his studies into child development, Jean Piaget suggested that children were born with an innate animist worldview in which they anthropomorphized inanimate objects and that it was only later that they grew out of this belief.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Conversely, from her ethnographic research, Margaret Mead argued the opposite, believing that children were not born with an animist worldview but that they became acculturated to such beliefs as they were educated by their society.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Stewart Guthrie saw animism—or "attribution" as he preferred it—as an evolutionary strategy to aid survival.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] He argued that both humans and other animal species view inanimate objects as potentially alive as a means of being constantly on guard against potential threats.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] His suggested explanation, however, did not deal with the question of why such a belief became central to the religion.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In the early 20th century, William McDougall defended a form of animism in his book *Body and Mind: A History and Defence of Animism* (1911).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] In *Error and Loss: A Licence to Enchantment* (2018) by Ashley Curtis it's argued that the Cartesian idea of an experiencing subject facing off with an inert physical world is incoherent at its very foundation and that this incoherence is consistent with rather than belied by Darwinism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Human reason (and its rigorous extension in the natural sciences) fits an evolutionary niche just as echolocation does for bats and infrared vision does for pit vipers, and is epistemologically on a par with, rather than superior to, such capabilities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] The meaning or aliveness of the "objects" we encounter, rocks, trees, rivers, and other animals, thus depends for its validity not on a detached cognitive judgment, but purely on the quality of our experience.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Harvey opined that animism's views on personhood represented a radical challenge to the dominant perspectives of modernity, because it accords "intelligence, rationality, consciousness, volition, agency, intentionality, language, and desire" to non-humans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Similarly, it challenges the view of human uniqueness that is prevalent in both Abrahamic religions and Western rationalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animist beliefs can also be expressed through artwork.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Harvey, therefore, argued that the creation of art among the Māori was not about creating an inanimate object for display, but rather a transformation of different persons within a relationship.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/animism] Animist worldviews have also been identified in the animated films of Hayao Miyazaki.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The **Anishinaabe** (alternatively spelled **Anishinabe**, **Anicinape**, **Nishnaabe**, **Neshnabé**, **Anishinaabeg**, **Anishinabek**) are a group of culturally related Indigenous peoples in the Great Lakes region of Canada and the United States.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] They include the Ojibwe (including Saulteaux and Oji-Cree), Odawa, Potawatomi, Mississaugas, Nipissing, and Algonquin peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe speak *Anishinaabemowin*, or Anishinaabe languages that belong to the Algonquian language family.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] At the time of first contact with Europeans they lived in the Northeast Woodlands and the Subarctic, and some have since spread to the Great Plains.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The word *Anishinaabe* means 'people from whence lowered'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Another definition is 'the good humans', meaning those who are on the right road or path given to them by the Creator Gitche Manitou, or Great Spirit.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Basil Johnston, an Ojibwe historian, linguist, and writer, wrote that the term's literal translation is 'beings made out of nothing' or 'spontaneous beings'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe believe that their people were created by divine breath.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The word *Anishinaabe* is often mistakenly considered a synonym of *Ojibwe*, but it refers to a much larger group of Nations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The name *Anishinaabe* is sometimes shortened to *Nishnaabe*, mostly by Odawa people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The cognate *Neshnabé* comes from the Potawatomi, a people long allied with the Odawa and Ojibwe in the Council of Three Fires.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Nipissing, Mississaugas, and Algonquin are identified as Anishinaabe but are not part of the Council of Three Fires.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Closely related to the Ojibwe and speaking a language mutually intelligible with *Anishinaabemowin* (Anishinaabe language) is the Oji-Cree (also known as "Severn Ojibwe").
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Their most common autonym is *Anishinini* (plural: *Anishininiwag*), and they call their language *Anishininiimowin*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Among the Anishinaabe, the Ojibwe collectively call the Nipissings and the Algonquins *Odishkwaagamii* 'those who are at the end of the lake', while those among the Nipissings who identify themselves as Algonquins call the Algonquins proper *Omàmiwinini* 'those who are downstream'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Not all Anishinaabemowin-speakers call themselves Anishinaabe.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Ojibwe people who migrated to what are now Canada's prairie provinces call themselves *Nakawē(-k)* and call their branch of the Anishinaabemowin *Nakawēmowin*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] (The French ethnonym for the group is *Saulteaux*.) Particular Anishinaabe groups have different names from region to region.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe use of the clan system represents familial, spiritual, economic and political relations between members of their communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Often an animal is used to represent a person's clan or *dodem* but plants and other spirit beings are sometimes used as well.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The word *dodem* means 'the heart or core of a person, village or community'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] There are different teachings about how many clans there are and which are clans in leadership positions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This is due to the decentralized mode of governance that the Anishinaabe practice.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Each person is a self-determining authority, and it is their duty to uphold their own roles and responsibilities for the wellbeing of *all our relations*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This is understood as the "Law of Non-interference".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Nobody can interfere with another being's path unless they are causing great harm to another or themselves.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Within the Anishinaabe governance structure there are seven leader clans that each facilitate a specific role and have responsibilities within the community and to the rest of Creation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Within each grouping of clans are seven clans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This means there are a total of 49 Anishinaabe clans.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The clan system is integral to the Anishinaabe governance structure and to the Anishinaabe way of life as well as to their spiritual practices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] People of the same clan are forbidden from marrying or having intimate relations as this would spell doom for the clan as a whole.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabe cultural tradition it is believed that human beings were created on the earth in four distinct places, in their own way.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This is what *Gizhe Mnidoo* or the Creator intended.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] There are many versions and parts to the Creation story that tell about the creation of the cosmos, the earth, the plants, the animals and human beings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] To Anishinaabe all life contains the sacred breath of life that was given by *Gizhe Mnidoo* and all things are animated through this sacred breath.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe give thanks for this gift of Creation through the burning or offering of tobacco (*semaa*).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Anishinaabe oral tradition and records of *wiigwaasabak* (birch bark scrolls) are still carried on today through the *Midewewin* society.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] These oral and written records contain the Anishinaabe creation stories as well as histories of migration that closely match other Indigenous groups of North America, such as the Hopi.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Before the Anishinaabe became Anishinaabe the people migrated from Waubanaukee, an island of the East Coast, which may have been what is now called New England, as the great ice sheet receded at the end of the last ice age.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This migrating group split in many different directions as they headed towards the land of the rising sun and became the many Indigenous populations that now exist on North America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After reaching the East Coast seven prophets came to the people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Each prophet delivered a specific prophecy to the people that are known as the seven fires prophecies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After the prophets delivered their messages, groups of people began to migrate westward to find the land where food grows on the water.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The fulfilment of this prophecy is understood as when the Anishinaabe found the wild rice (*mnoomin*) or that grew on the lakes in the Great Lakes region.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This is where the Anishinaabe became Anishinaabe.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] To the Anishinaabe, the land they encompass is still recognized as *Gitchi Mikinaak* or Turtle Island.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The ethnic identities of the Ojibwa, Odawa, and Potawatomi did not develop until after the Anishinaabe reached Michilimackinac on their journey westward from the Atlantic coast.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Using the *Midewewin* scrolls, Potawatomi elder Shop-Shewana dated the formation of the Council of Three Fires to 796 AD at Michilimackinac.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In this council, the Ojibwa were addressed as the "Older Brother", the Odawa as the "Middle Brother", and the Potawatomi as the "Younger Brother".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Consequently, when the three Anishinaabe nations are mentioned in this specific order: Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi, it implies the Council of Three Fires as well.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Each tribe had different functions: the Ojibwa were the "keepers of the faith", the Odawa the "keepers of trade," and the Potawatomi are the "keepers/maintainers of/for the fire" (*boodawaadam*).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] However, occasional unresolved disputes erupted into wars.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Odawa (also known as Ottawa or Outaouais) are a Native American and First Nations people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Ojibwe/Ojibwa, Chippewa, or *Anishinaabemowin* is the third most commonly spoken Native language in Canada (after Cree and Inuktitut).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Potawatomi is a Central Algonquian language.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] It is spoken around the Great Lakes in Michigan and Wisconsin, as well as in the U.S. state of Kansas.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In southern Ontario in Canada, it is spoken by fewer than 50 people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Though the Three Fires had several meeting places, they preferred *Michilimackinac* due to its central location.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe communities are recognized as First Nations in Canada.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The first of the Anishinaabe to encounter European settlers were those of the Three Fires Confederation, within the states of Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio, and Pennsylvania in the territory of the present-day United States, and southern Ontario and Quebec of Canada.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] There were many interactions between the Anishinaabe and the European settlers; the Anishinaabe dealt with Europeans through the fur trade and as allies in European-centered conflicts.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Europeans traded with the Anishinaabe for their furs in exchange for goods and also hired the Anishinaabe men as guides throughout the lands of North America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe women (as well as other indigenous groups) occasionally would intermarry with fur traders and trappers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Some of their descendants would later create a *Métis* ethnic group.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Explorers, trappers, and other European workers married or had unions with other Anishinaabe women, and their descendants tended to form a Métis culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The first Europeans to encounter Native Americans in the Great Lakes region were French explorers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] These men were professional canoe-paddlers (voyageurs) who transported furs and other merchandise over long distances in the lake and river system of northern America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Such explorers gave French names to many places in present-day Minnesota, Michigan and Wisconsin.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] French settlers in the region were primarily trappers and traders and rarely established permanent settlements due to the harsh North American climate.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In 1715, French military officer Constant le Marchand de Lignery constructed Fort Michilimackinac, in part to regulate relations with nearby Anishinaabe Indians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe came into contact with British colonists in the 17th and 18th centuries as they gradually expanded into the Great Lakes region as well.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Since the Iroquois had allied with the British Empire, the Anishinaabe fought numerous conflicts against them in conjunction with their French allies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] During the French and Indian War, the majority of the Anishinaabe fought with France against the British and their Indian allies, though after Britain's victory most of them sought peace with the British.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] However, dissatisfaction resulting from new British policies, in particular the cancellation of the annual distribution of gifts to the Indians, led to the formation of a pan-tribal confederation, composed of several Anishinaabe peoples, to counter British control of the Ohio Country.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The resulting conflict, known as Pontiac's War, resulted in a military stalemate that saw the British eventually adopting more conciliatory policies, issuing the Royal Proclamation of 1763, which forbade further white settlement across the American frontier.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After Pontiac's War, the Anishinaabe gradually established the same relationship with the British that they had with the French.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] During the American Revolution, which partly resulted from opposition in the Thirteen Colonies to the 1763 proclamation, the Anishinaabe (including the Three Fires Confederation) mostly sided against the rebelling colonists.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Fighting in conjunction with British and Loyalist forces, the Anishinaabe fought in the Northern and Western theaters of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After the British defeat in the Revolutionary War, the Anishinaabe mostly sought peace with the new United States, though lingering tensions resulting from encroachment by American settlers continued to spill into frequent outbreaks of violence in the frontier.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] During the Northwest Indian War and the War of 1812, the Three Fires Confederacy fought with the British against the United States.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Many Anishinaabe refugees from the Revolutionary War, particularly the Odawa and Potawatomi, migrated northwards to British North America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Those who remained east of the Mississippi River were subjected to the Indian removal policy of the United States government; among the Anishinaabe, the Potawatomi were most affected by the removals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Odawa had been removed from the migration paths of U.S. settlers, so only a handful of communities experienced removal.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] For the Ojibwa, removal attempts culminated in the Sandy Lake Tragedy, which resulted several hundred deaths.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Potawatomi avoided removal only by escaping into Ojibwa-held areas and hiding from U.S. officials.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] William Whipple Warren, an American man of mixed Ojibwe and European descent, became an interpreter, assistant to a trader to the Ojibwe, and legislator of the Minnesota Territory.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] A gifted storyteller and historian, he collected native accounts and wrote the *History of the Ojibway People, Based Upon Traditions and Oral Statements*, first published by the Minnesota Historical Society in 1885, some 32 years after his early death from tuberculosis.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Given his Anglo-American father, Lyman Marcus Warren, and American education, the Ojibwe of the time did not consider Warren one of them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] However, they retained friendly relations with him and considered him a half-brother due to his extensive knowledge of the Ojibwe language and culture and the fact that he had Ojibwe ancestry through his mixed Ojibwe-French mother, Marie Cadotte.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] His work covered much of the culture and history of the Ojibwe, gathered from stories of the Ojibwe Nation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Warren identified the Crane and Loon clans as the two Chief clans among his mother's Anishinaabe people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Crane Clan was responsible for external governmental relationships, and Loon Clan was responsible for internal governance relationships.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Warren believed that the policies of the U.S. government led to the destruction of indigenous clan systems along with their modes of governance when they forced indigenous people to adopt representative government and direct elections of chiefs.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Furthermore, he claimed that this destruction led to many wars among the Anishinaabe.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] He also cited the experiences of other indigenous nations in the U.S.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] (such as the Creek, Fox, and other peoples).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] His work was a major early work in demonstrating the significance of the clan system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After the Sandy Lake Tragedy, the U.S. government changed its policy to relocating tribes onto reservations, often by consolidating groups of communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Conflict continued through the 19th century, as Native Americans and the United States had different goals.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] After the Dakota War of 1862, many Anishinaabe communities in Minnesota were relocated and further consolidated.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] There are many Anishinaabe reserves and reservations; in some places, the Anishinaabe share some of their lands with others, such as the Cree, the Dakota, the Delaware, and the Kickapoo, among others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishnabe who "merged" with the Kickapoo tribe may now identify as being Kickapoo in Kansas and Oklahoma.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Prairie Potawatomi were the Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi of Illinois and Wisconsin who were relocated to Kansas during the 19th century.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe of Manitoba, particularly those along the east side of Lake Winnipeg, have had longstanding historical conflicts with the Cree people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In addition to other issues shared by First Nations recognized by the Canadian government and other aboriginal peoples in Canada, the Anishinaabe of Manitoba, Ontario and Quebec have opposed the Energy East pipeline of TransCanada.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Chippewas of the Thames First Nation legally challenged the right of the Canadian government to hold a pipeline hearing without their consent.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The project was also the basis of a June 2015 declaration of reclaimed sovereignty over the Ottawa River valley by several Anishinaabe peoples.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The relationship between the various Anishinaabe communities and the United States government has been steadily improving since the passage of the 1934 Indian Reorganization Act.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Several Anishinaabe communities still experience tensions with the state governments, county governments, and non-Native American individuals and their groups.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In this system originally, clans were represented by a changing cast of spokespeople at yearly meetings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In more recent times, clans have come to align personality characteristics with the animals that represent them.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This shifts the focus from extended family governance to groups of people who have a particular kind of strength to offer to the community.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] For example, the Deer Clan is sometimes understood as having the direction of hospitality toward visitors, whereas the Crane Clan or Eagle Clan, depending on region, may be aligned with leadership qualities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Conversations surrounding how to change current systems of governance to better match how the people governed themselves over millennia are always occurring throughout *Anishinaabe Aki* (their home territory).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Teachings of the Seven Grandfathers are among the most commonly shared teachings in Native culture.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] They hold great significance to the Anishinaabe and are considered to be the founding principles of their way of life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Seven Grandfather teachings have been around for centuries, passed on from elders through storytelling.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] These teachings have helped shape the way of life for the Anishinaabe for years and continue to do so.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The stories can be adapted to fit specific community values and have been incorporated by organizations, schools, different programs, artists, individualists, and tribes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, to cherish knowledge is to know wisdom.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Wisdom is given by the Creator to be used for the good of the people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabemowin, this word expresses not only 'wisdom' but also means 'prudence, intelligence'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In some communities, *Gikendaasowin* is used; in addition to 'wisdom', this word can also mean 'intelligence' or 'knowledge'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, to know peace is to know love.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] When people are weak they need love the most.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabemowin, this word with the reciprocal theme *idi* indicates that this form of love is mutual.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In some communities, *Gizhaawenidiwin* is used, which in most context means 'jealousy' but in this context is translated as either 'love' or 'zeal'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, to honor all creation is to have respect.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] All of creation should be treated with respect.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] If an individual wants to be respected, they must also show respect.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Some communities instead use *Ozhibwaadenindiwin* or *Manazoonidiwin*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, to be brave is to face the foe with integrity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabemowin, the word literally means 'state of having a fearless heart': to do what is right even when the consequences are unpleasant.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Some communities instead use either *Zoongadiziwin* ('state of having a strong casing') or *Zoongide'ewin* ('state of having a strong heart').
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, honesty in facing a situation is to be brave.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Individuals should always be honest in word and action.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] If an individual is honest with themselves first, they will more easily be able to be honest with others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabemowin, the word can also mean 'righteousness'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, humility requires recognizing oneself as a sacred part of Creation, neither better nor worse than any other creation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In Anishinaabemowin, the word can also mean 'compassion'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Some communities instead express this with *Bekaadiziwin*, which in addition to 'humility' can also be translated as 'calmness, meekness, gentility, patience'.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] According to Anishinaabe culture, truth is knowing all of these things.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Individuals should speak the truth and not deceive themselves or others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Anishinaabe follow an oral storytelling tradition.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Storytelling serves as an integral part of Anishinaabe culture as "stories teach the stock of wisdom and knowledge found in the culture" and "promotes 'respectful individualism," wherein individuals do not force their thinking upon others.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Instead of directly teaching right and wrong, the Anishinaabe often use storytelling to share their history and cultural truths, including but not limited to the Teachings of the Seven Grandfathers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] There is no need for any particular story to have any particular form.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Nor is it the case that any one story can ever be said to have achieved its final form.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Before telling a story, Elders "very often begin by quoting the authority of Elders who have gone before.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] They do not state the authority as coming from themselves.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Stories are typically shared throughout the winter when there is less to do and the animals are sleeping.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Trickster is a common character in Anishinaabe storytelling and goes by many names, including Coyote, Raven, Wesakejac, Nanabozho, and Glooscap.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Trickster helps teach cultural lessons by "learning lessons the 'hard' way." Within such stories, "Trickster often gets into trouble by ignoring cultural rules and practices or by giving sway to the negative aspects of 'humanness' ...
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Before the arrival of the Europeans, and until at least the 1800s, many Anishinaabe were subsistence farmers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] For example, the Odawa, centered in Michilimackinac, grew corn in the summers and generally moved south in smaller family groups in the winters to hunt game.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] They tapped sugar maples in the spring, and moved back to the main villages to prepare for the lake sturgeon spawning season and planting.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] They were renowned for their skills at making and using canoes and traded widely.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Their kinship was patrilineal and most Anishinaabe doodemag enforced exogamy, the wife keeping and representing her father's doodem while her children would take on their father's doodem.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] For the first few years of a marriage, a husband would live with his wife's family, and then they would typically return to the husband's people.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] As a result, many Anishinaabe villages included people speaking different languages not only from different clans, but also from entirely different peoples, such as the Huron and even occasionally Sioux.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The thunderbird is a common symbol used to represent the Anishinaabe.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Deleary of Chippewas of the Thames created a logo for what was then the Union of Ontario Indians.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] This logo features a black thunderbird in profile with an X-shaped body, in a circle.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] The Union of Ontario Indians later became the Anishinabek Nation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] A variant of the logo using a red background was officially adopted in 1980.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Both the white background and red background designs have been used as pan-Anishinaabe flags.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Different Anishinaabe political organizations have their own specific flags and emblems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] For example, the Menominee use a red thunderbird with a different styling for their great seal, whereas the Ho-Chunk flag depicts a thunderbird like a brown eagle.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] In August 2017 the Anishinabek Nation in Ontario and the government of Canada signed an agreement allowing the Anishinabek Nation to control the classroom curriculum and school resources of its kindergarten-to-grade-12 education system in 23 communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anishinaabe] Approximately 8% of Anishinabek students attend schools on-reserve.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They range from economic interests to ideological and political positions that are hostile towards environmental social and political change, including critical perspectives that encourage environmentalists to think about more inclusive approaches toward sustainability.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Criticism of environmentalism has taken different forms in different historical periods.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Many oppositions to environmentalism have arisen within the environmental movement itself, from the internal contrasts and debates.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] During the 1960s and 1970s, environmentalism was inspired by concerns about resource scarcity and over-exploitation: fear of the future well-being of humanity in relation to the planets health.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This concept is known as neo-Malthusianism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] These ideas came under criticism from neoclassical economists, who felt that the role of scientific and technological innovation in securing additional resources was overlooked.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some challenged the reliability of mathematical models, including that of the famous Club of Rome's Limits to Growth Report: critics argued that it had not adequately considered feedback and the effects of human decisions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Criticism also came from the left, for example from thinkers such as Murray Bookchin, who attributed environmental problems to political and social causes rather than natural resource scarcity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Marxist critics argued that environmentalist ideas, influenced by neo-Malthusianism, had racist, elitist, and imperialist overtones, and considered them reactionary.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Meanwhile, business interests affected by the rapidly expanding environmental legislations formed alliances to counter it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] These coalitions reflected the same methods of social and environmental movements: community-level mobilization and collaborative partnerships, as well as public awareness campaigns, media engagement, research publications, and providing testimony during hearings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] During the 1980s, environmentalism gained traction as a social and political force in many Western countries.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] National environmental legislation and international environmental initiatives grew in response to scientific findings.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Oppositions arose against perceived excesses among environmentalist positions (e.g., against apocalyptic visions of the future).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Radical and organized oppositions also arose in the form of countermovements.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The 1990s witnessed the full emergence of public relations applied to environmental issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The corporation-led coalition-building efforts from the 1970s continued to expand.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some corporations even went beyond their corporate allies by hiring specialized PR firms to establish front groups, creating the illusion of grassroots support for corporate interests to persuade politicians to oppose environmental reforms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Environmental public relations, often referred to as greenwashing, has become a lucrative industry for PR firms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Tactics that were enacted to defend Tobacco companies by minimizing or denying health effects are applied today by the fossil fuel industry; in some instances employing the same actors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] American companies now invest hundreds of millions of dollars annually in greenwashing and strategic counsel, which involves shaping public and governmental perceptions of environmental problems and devising strategies to counter environmentalists and regulations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Misinformation around climate change is spread via think tanks, political actors, influencers, conservative media creating information echo chambers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The United States, which since the 1970s had first developed models of environmental legislation later imitated around the world, has repeatedly seen the rise of pressure and initiatives to reduce environmental legislation among Republican politicians and administrations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Bush stated in his campaign platform that he would "ensure that the federal government, which is the country's largest polluter, complies with all environmental laws" and that the United States would even exceed the set standards.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Though once elected, Bush verged from what he had promised during his campaign, and instead reversed the initiatives of the previous Clinton administration on drinking water, and advocated for oil exploration in protected regions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Bush's administration also moved forward in withdrawing its support of the Kyoto Protocol, a worldwide global warming agreement created in 1997.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Bush stated that he would work with allies to the United States to reduce greenhouse gases, but would not carry out a plan that would "harm the economy" and "hurt American workers".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The conflict between support and opposition to environmental policies has become an important factor in the growing social and political polarization in the United States.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Anti-environmentalism is fueled by both social and economic reasons and ideological positions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The ideological underpinnings of anti-environmentalism can be very diverse and sometimes opposed to each other: from neoliberal to anti-capitalist ideologies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In some contexts, especially in the United States, anti-environmentalist social movements and initiatives are frequently inspired by conservative or neoliberal political ideologies: these favor a free market economy over government regulation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Such political positions find support in corporate interests that feel threatened by environmental concerns or environmental regulations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Although many observers of anti-environmentalism point out the frequent association between these initiatives and specific business interests threatened by environmental policies, others consider that there are cultural factors in certain social groups that underlie their anti-environmentalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This resistance is fueled by concern about political and cultural changes resulting from the social movements of the 1960s out of which environmentalism emerged.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some anti-environmentalist positions may arise from genuine anxiety related to the consequences of environmental regulations feared for the economic well-being of families and communities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Opposition to environmentalists may also be widespread among social sectors that see environmentalists as linked to urban life, alienated from local realities and knowledge, and closer to specialized knowledge.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Many experts argue that ideological explanations of anti-environmentalism, based on traditional concepts of the political left and right, are of little use in interpreting current political positions, especially regarding climate policies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Research in the social and political fields suggests that populist and nationalist ideologies are more relevant factors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In Europe, anti-environmentalism is widespread in the radical right and is generally associated with typical opposition to immigration, nationalism, welfare chauvinism (i.e., social policies must favor the country's citizens), and euroscepticism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The reasons behind the prevalent anti-environmentalism expressed by right-wing populists in Europe and North America are subject to debate and remain intricate.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] On one hand, economic and social factors play a role: a significant portion of these parties' supporters comprises individuals who have felt the economic impacts of globalization and modernization, viewing climate policies as linked to their struggles and exacerbating their situation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] On the other hand, ideological considerations come into play and can be categorized in two ways.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Firstly, there is a disdain for climate policies perceived as initiatives championed by liberal, globally oriented individuals who are seen as not prioritizing the nation's interests.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Secondly, there is a preference for a direct connection between ordinary citizens and those in positions of power.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The complexity of climate change, demanding intricate solutions, contrasts with their inclination toward simplicity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Additionally, there is a belief that figures in authority, including climate scientists and environmentalists, are influenced by special interests, fostering skepticism toward climate initiatives.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Opposition to environmentalism is often supported by corporations and coordinated through conservative think tanks, alongside sham public support campaigns (known as astroturfing) orchestrated by public relations firms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] These actors create links between corporate interests, conservative intellectuals, and segments of the public who share conservative perspectives or are concerned about the impact of environmental policies on communities and workers in specific sectors.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Conservative think tanks or sometimes academic researchers participate in the development of anti-environmentalist analysis and policy positions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Among the intellectuals and authors who have distinguished themselves internationally are Danish academic Bjørn Lomborg, Canadian former Greenpeace activist Patrick Moore, Canadian journalist Rex Murphy, and the US commentator Vivian Krause.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Public relations firms regularly assist the communication and lobbying of large companies whose interests are affected by environmental policies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some communications initiatives may support the establishment of social front groups capable of lobbying legislators to reduce environmental regulations.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Conservative foundations and philanthropic entities that fund anti-environmental initiatives are also active in the United States.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some of these institutional actors (e.g., Citizens for a Sound Economy, founded by entrepreneur David Koch) call themselves environmentalists and argue that traditional environmental groups have overstated environmental problems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They use green marketing techniques to convince the public of their high level of environmental responsibility.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In essence, these organizations create controversial information and call it environmental or green ideology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They frequently endorse campaigns to increase access to certain resources, such as forests and mines.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Think tanks associated with companies and seemingly independent groups can present themselves as autonomous research centers capable of providing expertise (analysis and communication) valued by the mass media.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The media gives them space to balance environmentalist perspectives.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] However, this process can lead the media to overemphasize scientific uncertainty on some environmental issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In other words, by presenting such sources as independent and reliable, the media may unintentionally amplify the perception of uncertainty, influencing public perceptions of specific environmental issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Other conservative think tanks (e.g., Cato Institute and The Heritage Foundation) address environmental issues as part of a broader agenda, including discussions of fiscal policy, energy, monetary policy, education, health care, and global economic liberalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They consider that many public interest or environmental regulations are counterproductive.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They support judicial activism to protect civil and economic liberties, an open and competitive energy market, and the importance of consumer choice and private incentives over a public approach to address real environmental concerns.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Many conservative think tanks involved in climate change, mineral resources, and indigenous rights issues are connected to the Atlas Network.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Since the 1980s, the Atlas Network has been a supporter of neoliberal ideas, promoting these through international networking and funding of conservative think tanks.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The organization operates globally, encompassing hundreds of think tanks across all continents.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The most widespread contemporary example of organized anti-environmentalism is the climate change denial or skepticism movement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Skeptics attack the evidence for climate change.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Skepticism can target the observed trend ("global warming does not exist"), the identification of causes ("warming exists, but humans are not responsible"), or the impact ("warming could be harmless or even beneficial").
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This kind of skepticism is intended to fuel uncertainty about climate science: the goal is to undermine scientific discourses of environmental policy or to confuse the public and policymakers.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Another type of skepticism is so-called response skepticism, that is, skepticism directed at actions taken to address climate change.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] It can be associated with climate denialism, but can also be expressed without opposing the evidence of climate change ("climate change exists and is caused by humans, but the prevailing responses are wrong or overly harmful").
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Climate skepticism is widespread among European parties of the far right and radical right.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] However, a study of the positions expressed by these parties in the European Parliament indicated that they rarely manifest climate denialism: opposition is more often directed at climate policies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Anti-environmentalist positions are intended to fuel a pro-sovereignist and anti-elite desire and speak to issues close to voters, such as economic welfare.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They also include pro-environmental and pro-climate positions and support for the fight against climate change.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They are accompanied by a critique of liberal climate policies as causing pollution, and of global capitalism and in favor of localism and economic nationalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The climate skeptic movement is supported by certain corporate or national interests that wish to maintain the profitability of economic sectors (especially those related to fossil fuels) in the face of growing environmental concerns.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] It also draws on anxieties about environmental protection among segments of the public that rely on fossil fuel-intensive economies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The countermovement is supported by a minority of scientists who have been visible promoters of climate science skepticism and by an extensive network of think tanks, which often also pursue other neoliberal or conservative agendas (e.g., against government regulation).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In the 1980s, the so-called "wise use" movement emerged, consisting of local groups mainly in the western part of North America.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This movement emerged as a diverse alliance of ranchers, miners, loggers, hunters, off-road vehicle drivers, oil workers, and farmers who, despite their differences, united against environmentalists.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They oppose public environmental management initiatives, which are perceived as authoritarian and detrimental to individual freedoms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They share the belief that a limited, non-interventionist government is more just, believing that a large bureaucracy threatens individual rights and freedoms.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They support the individual right to use natural resources as part of the right to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] They also support the development of national parks run by private companies and civil penalties for anyone who legally challenges economic activity or development on federal lands.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Some members have also supported violent actions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] External criticisms of environmentalism often arise from or are related to internal disputes between different currents within the movement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In particular, the tension between deep or ecosystem-centered ecology (accused of anti-humanism by external opponents) and humanist or social justice-oriented environmentalists has generated new perspectives that are more attentive to the social aspects of environmental choices.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The environmental justice perspective deals with the disproportionate and unjust distribution of environmental risks and harms within and among societies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In recent years, environmental social sciences, such as environmental history, political ecology, and environmental sociology, have been growing in importance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] These disciplines have contributed to a deepening understanding of the complex link between the environment and society.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] One example of this tension relates to the application of nature conservation models inspired by North American ideals of wilderness conservation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The use of such models in different contexts has caused conflicts with local traditions of land use.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This tension and the criticism of traditional conservation models have often led to an evolution of the models themselves, seeking to better integrate pre-existing relationships between local people and their land.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In general, in developing countries, local environmentalist ideas and actions are not necessarily influenced by the post-materialist perspectives of Western environmentalism.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] For communities in these countries, environmental challenges are often linked to struggles over natural resources, as in the case of disputes between farmers and companies over timber or between rural and urban residents over water and energy.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Such conflicts often focus on the environment, as poorer communities seek to preserve control over their natural resources to prevent them from being lost to increasing state control or the expanding market system.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] As a result of these debates and criticisms, environmentalism is changing the way it deals with environmental science and the management of environmental problems, moving away from intransigent principled positions and accepting the complexity of the issues.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This shift recognizes the uncertainties in establishing cause-and-effect relationships, especially when dealing with large-scale environmental problems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In addition, there is an increasing emphasis on understanding power dynamics, winners and losers in environmental change and legislation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Although some changes are taking place, traditional ways of thinking, such as neo-Malthusian, romantic, and catastrophist perspectives, persist in the environmental movement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The Alberta oil sands has also been a point of contention between environmentalists and those who exclusively consider economic growth to be important.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Anti-environmentalists maintain that the oil sands have improved Canada's relations with the United States as Canada is their number one foreign supplier of oil.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] As well, the oil sands have brought a secure source of energy to Canada, as well as tremendous economic gains for Alberta.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] There are environmental efforts in place to mitigate the effects that the mining involved in operating the oil sands mine has on animal species, though some environmentalist groups are not satisfied.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Environmentalist groups such as Greenpeace are concerned with the environmental, social and health impacts of mining the oil sands, particularly on First Nations communities in Alberta.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The source of this conflict is that on January 25, 2016, Dakota Access announced that it received permit approval to move forward with the construction of a four-state crude oil pipeline which would transport 470,000 barrels of oil per day from North Dakota to Illinois.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Anti-environmentalists defended the construction of the Pipeline as it would create thousands of jobs, make the United States more energy independent and create a more cost-effective method of transporting oil to major refining markets.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The Standing Rock Sioux Tribe took issue with this as the pipeline would run through their communities, tainting their sacred land as well as contaminating their water supply.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] What followed in the next ten months was a response from Sioux communities, protestors and environmentalist groups in the form of peaceful protests in which over 400 arrests were made by local law enforcement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] 26 Environmentalist groups responded to the event with an open letter condemning the actions of the North American banks who helped fund the pipeline, and encouraged them to stop any future payments contributing to it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In 1991, Plzeň, Czech Republic experienced immense air pollution that citizens felt was the source of their health problems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The government decided they needed to build a new highway so the traffic could no longer create pollution in the city.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Two different plans were created, one being the K variant which put the highway south of the city, and the S variant which would go through protected land, and would have negative impacts on rural areas as opposed to the city.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This event began environmental movements in the Czech Republic that protested the S variant.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In previous years, Czechoslovakia had been focused on the Soviet model of industrial expansion which lacked environmental regulation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This had effects on the environment, such as low-grade coal used in houses and by industries as well as lead gasoline used in automobiles.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In the 1980's environmental activists protested the governments lack of environmental regulation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Political campaigns thereafter became increasingly anti-environmental through media outlets and newspaper coverage.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Media coverage shared statements such as "Environmentalists believe that bugs are more important than people" and "Beware of environmentalists – they are extremists." These statements created fear of environmental causes in the population.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In 2014, Environment Canada released its annual emissions trends report, which showed that Canada was not going to meet emission reduction targets as was promised in 2009.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In fact, Canada is on track to increase its emissions up until 2020.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Harper's government, while committed to reducing emissions over the long term, disapproved of limiting oil and gas emissions as the price of oil rose higher.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] This was consistent with Harper's decision to withdraw Canada from the Kyoto Protocol in 2011.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The main reason given for this by Harper was that Canada was not having success in meeting the protocol's targets.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In the following years, Harper's administration made it difficult for foreign-based environmental groups to obstruct Canadian economic growth.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Environmental charities experienced frequent audits by the federal government which resulted in less productivity and being at risk of losing their charitable status.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Harper also repealed a significant environmental policy which had previously been in place; the *Canadian Environmental Assessment Act*.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Later, a new version of the act was created.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In 2015, with the election of Justin Trudeau, the environment became one of Canada's main concerns, with Trudeau eventually signing the Paris Agreement in 2016, and has been aggressive at curtailing the oil and gas industry.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Former President Barack Obama promised to make the United States more environmentally conscious, and implemented the Clean Power Plan, invested significantly in clean energy, and improved standards for fuel economy of vehicles; this reduced pollution and was also economical.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Obama also made a joint agreement with China to reduce the emissions of both countries, and to reduce emissions in the United States by 27% by 2025.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The state of environmental affairs in the United States changed drastically under the Donald Trump administration.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Trump had been open about his plans to alter or withdraw entirely from many climate change and environmental agreements the United States was then involved in, such as the Paris Agreement.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] As this agreement is voluntary, the United States faced no penalty for declining to participate.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] However, as the United States is the second largest emitter of carbon after China, their lack of participation in the agreement would greatly impact global efforts to reduce carbon emissions.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] While in 1999, President Bill Clinton announced that the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) would enforce the toughest standards to date, Trump's administration instructed the Environmental Protection Agency to remove the climate change page from its website.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] EPA employees stated at the time that if the page were to be taken down, years of research on global warming would be gone, as well as detailed data on emissions and links to scientific global warming research.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] On June 1, 2017, Trump announced that the U.S. would cease all participation in the Paris Agreement on climate change mitigation.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In China, the city of Maoming became the focus of an environmental dispute in 2014, relating to the municipal government-sponsored Para-Xylene (PX) industry - a chemical used in manufacturing plastics, such as those in water bottles and polyesters.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The industry has been promoted in Maoming for its economic benefits due to the jobs provided by the factories.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Despite the industry's economic benefits, citizens organized PX protest in 2014 as there was increasing concern for the chemical's environmental and health risks to the citizens of the city.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] In June 2023, Minister of the Interior Gérald Darmanin announced that the French government would be forcibly dissolving the Les Soulèvements de la Terre.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] The announcement came following a series of raids by anti-terrorist police against the group, resulting in 18 arrests.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/anti-environmentalism] Human Rights Watch stated that the dissolution was "wholly disproportionate" and was part of "a growing trend of stigmatization and criminalization of individuals and civil society organizations raising awareness about the consequences of climate change" in France under Emmanuel Macron.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] The **biophilia hypothesis** (also called BET) suggests that humans possess an innate tendency to seek connections with nature and other forms of life.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Wilson introduced and popularized the hypothesis in his book, *Biophilia* (1984).
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] He defines biophilia as the "innate tendency to focus on life and lifelike processes".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] He argued that "to explore and affiliate with life is a deep and complicated process in mental development.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] To an extent still undervalued in philosophy and religion, our existence depends on this propensity, our spirit is woven from it, hope rises on its currents".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Wilson saw modern biology as converging with biophilia: "Modern biology has produced a genuinely new way of looking at the world that is incidentally congenial to the inner direction of biophilia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] In other words, instinct is in this rare instance aligned with reason.... to the degree that we come to understand other organisms, we will place a greater value on them, and on ourselves".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] "Biophilia" is an innate affinity of life or living systems.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] The term was first used by Erich Fromm to describe a psychological orientation of being attracted to all that is alive and vital.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Wilson uses the term in a related sense when he suggests that biophilia describes "the connections that human beings subconsciously seek with the rest of life." He proposed the possibility that the deep affiliations humans have with other life forms and nature as a whole are rooted in our biology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Both positive and negative (including phobic) affiliations toward natural objects (species, phenomenon) as compared to artificial objects are evidence for biophilia.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Although named by Fromm, the concept of biophilia has been proposed and defined many times over.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Aristotle was one of many to put forward a concept that could be summarized as "love of life".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Diving into the term *philia*, or friendship, Aristotle evokes the idea of reciprocity and how friendships are beneficial to both parties in more than just one way, but especially in the way of happiness.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] The hypothesis has since been developed as part of theories of evolutionary psychology.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Taking on an evolutionary perspective, people being drawn towards life and nature can be explained in part due to our evolutionary history of residing in natural environments, as only recently in our history have we shifted towards an urbanized lifestyle.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] These connections to nature can still be seen in people today as people gravitate towards, identify with, and desire to connect with nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] These connections are not limited to any one component part of nature, as people show connections to a wide range of natural things including plants, animals, and environmental landscapes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] One possible explanation is that our ancestors who had stronger connections to nature would hold an evolutionary advantage over less connected people as they would have better knowledge and therefore access to food, water, and shelter.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] In a broader and more general sense research has suggested that our modern urban environments are not suited for minds that evolved in natural environments.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Human preferences toward things in nature, while refined through experience and culture, are hypothetically the product of biological evolution.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] For example, adult mammals (especially humans) are generally attracted to baby mammal faces with their large eyes and rounded features and find them appealing across species.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Similarly, the hypothesis helps explain why ordinary people care for and sometimes risk their lives to save domestic and wild animals, and keep plants and flowers in and around their homes.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] In the book *Children and Nature: Psychological, Sociocultural, and Evolutionary Investigations* edited by Peter Kahn and Stephen Kellert, the importance of animals, especially those with which a child can develop a nurturing relationship, is emphasized particularly for early and middle childhood.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] The same book reports on the help that animals can provide to children with autistic-spectrum disorders.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Fractal fluency is a neuroscience model that proposes that, through exposure to nature's fractal scenery, people's visual systems have adapted to efficiently process fractals with ease.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Fractals are patterns that repeat at different scales.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Examples in natural scenery include clouds, mountains and trees.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] This adaptation to fractal patterns occurs at many stages of the visual system, from the way people's eyes move to which regions of the brain get activated.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Fluency puts the viewer in a ‘comfort zone’ so inducing an aesthetic experience.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Humans appear to be especially well-adapted to processing fractal patterns with fractal dimension between 1.3 and 1.5.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] When humans view fractal patterns with fractal dimensions in this range, these fractals reduce physiological stress and boost cognitive abilities.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Biophilic fractals are patterns designed to induce the health and well-being benefits associated with exposure to nature's scenery.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] These include stress-reduction and enhanced cognitive capacity.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Designers and architects incorporate biophilic fractals into the built environment to counter the fact that people spend 92% of their time indoors and away from nature's scenery.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] The Fractal Chapel designed by INNOCAD architecture in the state hospital in Graz, Austria, is a prominent example and recipient of the 2025 IIDA (International Interior Design Association) Best of Competition Award.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Many Indigenous cultures do not draw a sharp distinction between humans and nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] In these traditions, humans may be understood as an integral part of the natural world rather than as separate from it.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Human practices and ways of life may be seen to be based in relationships of reciprocity involving all living beings and the environment.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] At the heart of such belief systems is the concept of kinship, which extends beyond human relationships and includes elements of the natural world.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Humans, other animals, plants and soil are seen as dependent on each other for survival and health.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] For example, the Haudenosaunee people express this idea through a "Thanksgiving Address", a ceremony intended to honor all aspects of nature.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Some Indigenous cultures have developed what has been referred to as "traditional ecological knowledge".
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] This may include ostensibly sustainable stewardship practices such as controlled burns of vegetation, as employed in some traditional Native American and Aboriginal Australian societies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] In Hawaii, the idea of Aloha_ʻĀina aloha has served as a guide for responsible resource use.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Indigenous and animist beliefs typically view nature as sacred.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Specific sites, species, or phenomena holding deep significance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] Emphasis is put on objectives such as reciprocity and balance.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] This may imply an idea of nature restoration through sustainable practices, rituals, and ceremonies.
[src:biophilia-hypothesis/biophilia-hypothesis] For instance, the Anishinaabe make offerings before harvesting wild rice.
